<DOC><DOCNO> AP880720-0092 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0655EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-China-Heat     07-20 0187</FIRST><SECOND>PM-China-Heat,0192</SECOND><HEAD>Heat Wave Kills 71 in Shanghai</HEAD><DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The blistering heat wave that has broiled theYangtze River area of China this month has killed 71 people inShanghai, an official Chinese report said.   Hospitals in the Shanghai area also reported treating 353patients, mostly the infirm and elderly, for heat stroke as ofSunday, a China News Service article appearing in Hong Kong onWednesday said.   The mercury soared to 100 degrees in Shanghai on Sunday, thehighest yet this year, but by Tuesday had cooled under theinfluence of a typhoon that approached the southern China coast.   The report warned, however, that after two or three days ofcooler weather the heat wave could return.   The Shanghai death toll, which the news service attributed toreports coming from two funeral homes, brings to more than 400 thenumber of people who have died in the searing heat along theYangtze River.   Official media has reported 290 elderly people died in thesouthern city of Nanchang and 83 people died from the heat inNanjing, the capital of coastal Jiangsu province.</TEXT></DOC>